{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17651683","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17651683"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:26:34+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:26:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18484"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18484","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18484"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11213"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76090"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11213","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11213"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18484"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61591"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"},{"type":"tags","id":"7492"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26036"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26263"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76090","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76090"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe ear contains several openings and passages that allow sound transmission and maintenance of pressure equilibrium.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the oval window of the ear?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Opening between external and middle ear","Connection between cochlea and vestibular system","Membrane-covered opening between middle and inner ear","Opening between two cochlear ducts","Opening between nasopharynx and middle ear"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Emembrane-covered opening between middle and inner ear\u003C/strong\u003E correctly describes the oval window (image), located in the inner ear\u0027s lateral wall. The footplate of the stapes attaches to this membrane-covered opening, allowing sound vibrations to be transmitted into the fluid-filled inner ear.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOpening between external and middle ear\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes the tympanic membrane\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConnection between cochlea and vestibular system\u003C/strong\u003E - While both systems are part of the inner ear, they are not directly connected through the oval window\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOpening between two cochlear ducts\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes the helicotrema, which connects the scala tympani and scala vestibuli at the apex of the cochlea\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOpening between nasopharynx and middle ear\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes the auditory tube (Eustachian tube)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe oval window is essential for sound transmission as it allows mechanical vibrations of the ossicles to be converted into fluid waves in the perilymph of the inner ear.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The oval window is a membrane-covered opening in the lateral wall of the inner ear that transmits sound vibrations from the middle ear to the inner ear.","The footplate of the stapes bone attaches to the oval window membrane.","The oval window connects the middle ear to the vestibule of the inner ear, specifically to the scala vestibuli of the cochlea."],"references":["Netter FH. Netter Atlas of Human 